eKMSH_aKjGAJDHg2hfcUF5g74fkQLVro_oOigOqVw48Wucq28-a0cuujhHY8pBoM3Y6BOeHJjwuGggYDp3XmJuIiVZjB0E67QbrMqYdX7VkcKxXqo9TydlHG2ugR7-UVTaWpZEnDADZiqxqkJHyhO-Obs6wJn3yc_Ry9yRfcCkZEVIUNfvcVjqqIShKaiHDIRKI8II7Nnakyf1JZbZ8BoAz7t9Uf93Bojly6zOhG7a45FuqXQ_gqzYOQ_E0amgv0vPMU2ldZqA4-BnPZYSqLxoISnugXAeloFtJcDELdtKOqyjpIqKsfjjtCgf742jUB876ez2q_tI=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining invocation wrappers**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to handle invocation wrappers properly. If a method's invocation wraps an error in an InvocationTargetException, I'll need to unwrap that. If the cause is an error and unsupported, I should swallow it; but if the cause is just an exception, I may need to rethrow it. It’s all about managing those exceptions effectively, which can be a bit tricky at times!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test methods**\\n\\nI’m considering existing tests that use class generation but don’t incorporate test reflection. I wonder if it’s possible to add metadata, but coverage might not be relevant to metadata. Maybe direct reflection could require metadata since the agent captures it. For Native Image, it seems the tests utilize a test run agent that helps build native configurations. The GraalVM TCK plugin likely runs JVM tests with the agent first, which I think we can trust.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_TsLNEGubSYULlzj8HotAWixh|fc_0363e61edc4a913f0169f529cbfbb481a2858ad7b4294d82f0", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"sourceCompatibility|targetCompatibility|release\" build.gradle gradle -n | head -50"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 522, "output": 1681, "cacheRead": 34816, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 37019, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777674675126, "responseId": "resp_0363e61edc4a913f0169f529b39f1481a29033ddd1f40f551a"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolR